n prominence until the early 1980s. In 1968 Goldberg created the Computer Service, Inc. corporation, employing 8 programmers who developed programs that managed many aspects of the design and construction process, including door trajectories, room layouts, specification writing and error-proofing. The use of computers in Prentice greatly accelerated the design timeline and allowed for a more daring design than had previously been attempted in his hospitals, one in which four pods were cantilevered from a central core that carried through to the ground, eliminating the need for any columns to penetrate the rectilinear base. Despite their usefulness, Goldberg was quite aware of the computer's limitations, concluding that you couldn't \"put problems into the computer and get solutions... which hadn't previously existed in our heads.\"","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_002287.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"45.990234375","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Architecture for Urbanism: Selections from the Bertrand Goldberg Archive,\" Case 7, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, November 1, 2011\u2013January 2, 2012<br \/>\n<br \/>\n<a href=&quot;https:\/\/digital-libraries.artic.edu\/u?\/mqc,14881&quot;>Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record<\/a>","resource_tags_for_resource_id":"architecture, Chicago"},"resource_2288":{"resource_link":"..\/2288","resource_url":"http:\/\/www.artic.edu\/aic\/collections\/citi\/resources\/Rsrc_002288.jpg","resource_title":"09. Northwestern Memorial Hospital, Prentice Women's Hospital and Maternity Center, Chicago, IL. Construction view, [1974].","resource_description":"333 E. Superior, Chicago, IL, 1969-1975.","resource_f